            "creation_date": 1362356991,
            "body": "<p>Javascript - there are frameworks that could help ease the burden. The scenario you have described is an Ajax call to some service. You could represent the data as json which would be lightweight and easy enough to add to the page using javascript.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 15192716,
            "question_id": 15192644
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c56d2be4610150b3ca6441a8a237dcf5?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 106363,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 283361,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/283361/zach-riggle",
                "reputation": 3115,
                "display_name": "Zach Riggle",
                "accept_rate": 67
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1363136798,
            "creation_date": 1363121748,
            "body": "<p><a href=\"http://emberjs.com\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Ember.js<\/a> (specifically its <a href=\"http://emberjs.com/guides/models/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Models<\/a>) and <a href=\"http://grails.org\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Grails<\/a> do <strong>exactly<\/strong> what you want when used together.  I'm sure that you can use any Java framework to do this, but Grails makes it <strong>stupidly<\/strong> easy.  Below are a few patterns to get you started, but <a href=\"https://github.com/kentbutler/todomvc-grails-emberjs\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">here's a complete example app<\/a>!<\/p>\n\n<p>Domain class:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class Person {\n    String name\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Controller:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class PersonsController {\n    def index() { render ([\"person\": Person.list()] as JSON) }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Ember.js App:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>App.Store = DS.Store.extend({\n   revision: 11,\n   adapter:  DS.RESTAdapter.create({\n    namespace: 'app'\n  })\n)};\nApp.Person = DS.Model.extend({\n    name: DS.attr('string')\n)};\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>In your browser, this single command will populate the in-browser data store by fetching <code>/app/persons<\/code> from the backend.  Modifying the in-browser instances will automatically HTTP <code>POST<\/code> the updated instance to your Controller.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>App.Person.list()\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>You'll want to check out <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/15307576/how-to-make-ember-js-behave-with-grails-controller-names\">my answer on getting the two to play together in perfect harmony<\/a> for more complex applications.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 15371954,
            "question_id": 15192644,
            "last_edit_date": 1495535148
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5d6b3a89e2285cbac391d4b4cc564d93?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 2483912,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2162778,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2162778/david-muruli",
                "reputation": 21,
                "display_name": "David Muruli"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1363120359,
            "creation_date": 1363120359,
            "body": "<p>Abdull have you looked at GWT(Google  Web ToolKit) <a href=\"http://bit.ly/YYz2Yx\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://bit.ly/YYz2Yx<\/a>?<\/p>\n\n<p>Here is some sample code that illustrates creation of client side components.<\/p>\n\n<p>e.g. loading contacts<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>            VerticalPanel contactsPanel = new VerticalPanel();\n            contactsPanel.setSpacing(4);\n            String[] contactNames = constants.cwStackPanelContacts();\n            String[] contactEmails = constants.cwStackPanelContactsEmails();\n            for (int i = 0; i &lt; contactNames.length; i++) {\n              final String contactName = contactNames[i];\n              final String contactEmail = contactEmails[i];\n              final Anchor contactLink = new Anchor(contactName);\n              contactsPanel.add(contactLink)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://bit.ly/12MOhZQ\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://bit.ly/12MOhZQ<\/a> (for actual code sample)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 15371535,
            "question_id": 15192644
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e9f2225548b6d4c0f6f0dd4e202c1158?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 998783,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1014091,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1014091/mike-adler",
                "reputation": 1200,
                "display_name": "Mike Adler",
                "accept_rate": 83
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1363121037,
            "creation_date": 1363121037,
            "body": "<p>If you were not limited to the browser - and thus javascript, I'd scream RMI about now. Luckily, there seems to be a solution to make it work. I have not tried it, but it might be worthwhile:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>jabsorb is a simple, lightweight JSON-RPC library for communicating\n  between Javascript running in the browser and Java running on the\n  server. It allows you to call Java methods on the server from\n  Javascript as if they were local, complete with automatic parameter\n  and result serialization.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://code.google.com/p/jabsorb/\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://code.google.com/p/jabsorb/<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 15371750,
            "question_id": 15192644
        },
        {
            "owner": {
